Creating replacement function to streamline the genie

# Function to replace a word in a target data frame with a replacement word
replace_words <- function(text, replacements_25) {
 # Replace each bad word with its corresponding good word
 for (i in seq_len(nrow(replacements_25))) {
   text <- gsub(
     pattern = replacements_25$word[i],
     replacement = replacements_25$replacement[i],
     x = text,
     ignore.case = TRUE
   )
 }
 return(text)
}
#note: this ONLY works if the apostrophe's between the two dataframes are identical. E.g. ' is not recognized as matching the apostrophe's on the replacements_25 list, which look like this  .

Cleaning Genie Function

#Cleaning Genie function
cleaning_genie <- function(x){ #stating the function
   y <- tolower(x) #makes all lower case
   y <- stringi::stri_replace_all_regex(y, "[\u2018\u2019\u02BC\u201B\uFF07\u0092\u0091\u0060\u00B4\u2032\u2035]", "'") #replaces 18 different types of apostrophe with a standard unicode apostrophe
   y <- replace_words(y, replacements_25) #replaces contractions with full words
   y <- gsub('[[:punct:]]',' ', y) #removing all punctuation
   y <- gsub("\\b[a-zA-Z]\\b{1}", " ", y) #omits singletons including Aa and Ii
   y <- textstem::lemmatize_strings(y) #lemmatizes text
   y <- gsub('[0-9]+',' ', y) #removing all numbers
   y <- tibble(y) #making into a dataframe for the final piece!
   y <- y %>% unnest_tokens(word, y)  # one word per rows, removing blank spaces, and making all lowercase
   y <- y %>% anti_join(SMART_stops) #removing stop words by line
   return(y) #final step of the function
}

Importing unabomber to Quanteda package

unabomb_clean_flat <- unabomb_clean %>% summarize(full_text = str_flatten(word, " ")) #using summarise() to create a new df with a row for each combination of grouping variables. Since there are no grouping variable, the output is just a single row with all observations. str_flatten() lets us tell the column being summarized to put a space in between each string.

unabomb_clean_corp <- quanteda::corpus(unabomb_clean_flat, text_field = "full_text") #using the quanteda::corpus() function to convert df into a corpus. The argument text_field() tells quanteda which column of the df to summarize as a corpus.

#saving og unabomber manifesto as a df so that it can be properly read by quanteda
unabomb_flat <- unabomb %>% 
  tibble(unabomb) %>% #turning unabomb into a df
  summarize(full_text = str_flatten(unabomb, " ")) #creating a new df with one column called "full_text" with one row that contains the entire manifesto and putting a space between each string. 

#converting to a quanteda corpus (same as unabomb_clean_corp)
unabomb_corp  <- quanteda::corpus(unabomb_flat, text_field = "full_text")

Table of lexical characteristics pre/post

This prints two tables. The first is a table containing 2 versions of type token ratio (TTR), or the ratio of unique words compared to the entire text. TTR is traditional, but also includes the Mean Segmental Type-Token Ratio, which splits the tokens into segments of the given size, TTR for each segment is calculated and the mean of these values returned.

The corpus summary table and the TTR tables are then combined for ease of reading the overall lexical characteristics

# Create a tokenized version of the unabomber corpus for analyses
unabomb_token <- quanteda::tokens(unabomb_corp, remove_punct = TRUE)

#lexical diversity, can take a dfm or corpus
unabomb_ttrs <- textstat_lexdiv(unabomb_token, measure = c("TTR", "MSTTR"), log.base = 10)

# Create a tokenized version of the clean unabomber corpus for analyses
unabomb_clean_token <- quanteda::tokens(unabomb_clean_corp, remove_punct = TRUE)

#lexical diversity, can take a dfm or corpus
unabomb_clean_ttrs <- textstat_lexdiv(unabomb_clean_token, measure = c("TTR", "MSTTR"), log.base = 10)

#creating table with the summary and lexical diversity stats
all_unabomb_ttrs <- rbind(unabomb_ttrs, unabomb_clean_ttrs) 
print(all_unabomb_ttrs)
##        document       TTR     MSTTR
## 1       unabomb 0.1219891 0.6959118
## 2 unabomb_clean 0.1650518 0.7625281
#creating lexical characteristics table
unabomb_qualities <- all_unabomb_sum %>% dplyr::left_join(all_unabomb_ttrs, by = c("Text" = "document")) 
print(unabomb_qualities)
## Corpus consisting of 1 document, showing 1 document:

Lexical Dispersion Plot (5 words)

Creating a plot showing at what points in the text the selected words appear

textplot_xray(      #shows where keywords of interest appear throughout the document using an x-ray plot
    kwic((unabomb_clean_token), pattern = "society"), #using the quanteda kwic function to search for keywords
    kwic((unabomb_clean_token), pattern = "power"),
    kwic((unabomb_clean_token), pattern = "technology"),
    kwic((unabomb_clean_token), pattern = "industrial"),
    kwic((unabomb_clean_token), pattern = "freedom"),
    scale = "absolute"
)
